            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Samira Khan Volkov\u2019s identity was forged in a Chicago home filled with the aromas of her Pakistani father\u2019s biryani and the sound of her Russian-American mother\u2019s mournful folk songs. This duality taught her to see every story from multiple angles, a skill that naturally led her to a journalism degree. During an early internship covering city budgets, she realized the most powerful narratives weren't in quotes, but buried in spreadsheets. This epiphany charted her course toward data journalism.\n\nA painful breakup in her mid-twenties became the catalyst for a fresh start. Drawn by the tech industry\u2019s data gold rush and the promise of a city that celebrated complexity, she moved to San Francisco eight years ago. Landing a job at a prominent online news organization, she quickly distinguished herself by transforming raw data into compelling stories about Bay Area inequality. A key turning point was her expos\u00e9 on the disparate impact of transit delays on low-income neighborhoods, which won her a regional award and solidified her career.\n\nNow 33, Samira\u2019s life is a map of disciplined routines. Her day begins with a strong coffee in her Mission District apartment before she catches the 14-Mission bus for the 3.8-mile commute to her SoMa office. At work, she\u2019s a digital detective, wrangling datasets to uncover patterns of injustice. Socially, she relies on a tight-knit group of friends\u2014a mix of tech workers and artists who serve as her chosen family.\n\nSamira\u2019s connection to San Francisco is one of a critical observer. She loves the city for its breathtaking views and vibrant culture but is acutely aware of its deep-seated problems, which she documents daily. Her aspiration is to lead a Pulitzer-worthy investigative project that uses data to force meaningful policy change. Privately, she hopes to find a partner who understands her quiet intensity and, one day, to travel the Trans-Siberian Railway with her mother, connecting with the other half of her heritage."
